content: I want to thank everyone that donated money to send to Faye Pollard and her sister Betty Coats.  These ladies are in Tucson Arizona with their brother Ray Pruitt. The ACES Rock Competition is back with a twist!  ACES Rock Tac Toe! ‚ùå‚≠ïÔ∏è 

Beginning tomorrow, April 15 after school, 36 ACES themed rocks will be hidden throughout Hicksville.  Each rock will be worth 25 House Points and should be submitted to a staff House Leader - Mr. Stevenson, Mrs. Geiger, Mrs. Finzer or Mr. Gaghan.

Each rock turned in by a student will act as turn for their corresponding Senior House Leader in Otrio (a four-way Tic Tac Toe Game). We encourage you to get outside and find as many rocks as you can early in the competition while they are worth more but also to help your House Leader have a better chance of winning the Rock Tac Toe 250 Point Bonus!

üî∏ Members of CCPO Take Part in Operation Helping Hand Impact Series in Brooklawnüî∏

Brooklawn, N.J.- On May 16, 2023, the Camden County Prosecutor‚Äôs Office in partnership with the Volunteers of America Delaware Valley, and the Brooklawn Police Department hosted the OPERATION HELPING HAND COMMUNITY IMPACT SERIES in Brooklawn, at the Brooklawn Shopping Center.

CCPO staff including members of the Community Outreach and Engagement Unit and detectives took part in the Operation Helping Hand Community Impact Series event that is designed to address an individuals‚Äô personalized needs and demonstrate a commitment to assisting Camden County residents who are struggling with substance use disorder or are in need of guidance in obtaining social services.

At each Operation Helping Hand Community Impact Series event, Maryville and Volunteers of America Delaware Valley will offer residents assistance in obtaining the following:

*Mental Health and Substance Abuse Treatment

*Housing

*Identification

*Veterans Services

*Medical Treatment Linkage

*Benefits

*Reentry Services

*Care Management

If you, a friend, or a family member is in need of services, please join us at the NEXT Operation Helping Hand Community Impact Series event to be held on Wednesday, May 24, 2023, from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m., at the Wayne Bryant Community Center, at 323 East Charleston Avenue, Lawnside, NJ 08045.

On April 8, 2024, a total solar eclipse will cross North America, passing over Mexico, the United States, and Canada, with possible impacts in our area between 12:35 pm and 3:13 pm. 

A total solar eclipse happens when the Moon passes between the Sun and Earth, completely blocking the face of the Sun. In the Path of Totality, the sky will darken as if it were dawn or dusk. Pensacola will NOT experience a total solar eclipse as we are NOT in the path of totality. From Pensacola, only 80% of the sun will be eclipsed by the moon. Our skies will NOT darken significantly and will appear normal throughout the eclipse window. The sun will remain bright and should NOT be viewed directly at any time. 

All outdoor activities not approved by school principals will be suspended during these times, and school personnel will review with students proper safety protocols during the eclipse. Approved activities will vary by school and teacher and can include viewing the eclipse through approved eyewear and/or viewing the eclipse indirectly using pinhole projection. Teachers have received training on these topics. 

ECPS would urge families to review with their students some solar eclipse safety basics:
Always supervise children using solar viewers. 
Do NOT look at the Sun through a camera lens, telescope, binoculars, or any other optical device while wearing eclipse glasses or using a handheld solar viewer ‚Äî the concentrated solar rays will burn through the filter and cause serious eye injury.

Detectives Investigate Single-Vehicle Fatal Collision in Fairland:

Detectives from the Montgomery County Department of Police ‚Äì Collision Reconstruction Unit (CRU) are investigating a single-vehicle fatal collision that occurred this morning in the Fairland area.    

Today, Monday, April 12, at approximately 5:26 a.m., 3rd District officers and Montgomery County Fire and Rescue personnel responded to Columbia Pike (Route US-29) and Briggs Chaney Road for a report of a serious collision.    

Preliminary investigation has determined that a 2011 Toyota RAV4 was traveling north on Columbia Pike.  For reasons still under investigation, the Toyota RAV4 left the roadway and struck a concrete wall on the right side of the roadway.    

The driver and sole occupant of the Toyota RAV 4, Anavela Marizol Gordillo Cruz, age 56, of Kensington, was transported to a local hospital where she succumbed to her injuries. 

The Collision Reconstruction Unit (CRU) continues to investigate this collision.  Anyone with information regarding this collision is asked to contact CRU detectives at 240-773-6620.

Be On The Lookout: The Grinch has been spotted trying to impersonate Santa. Remember, if Santa starts taking for your presents instead of delivering them, it's not the real deal. Stay vigilant, folks! Follow these package theft prevention tips to help keep your holiday purchases safe: 

‚Ä¢Schedule packages to arrive when you're home.

‚Ä¢ Have your packages delivered to a location where someone can receive them in-person. A neighbor or relative who is usually home, for example, or your workplace if your employer allows it.

‚Ä¢Use an Amazon Locker.

‚Ä¢ Encourage your neighbors to watch for deliveries and agree to secure each other‚Äôs packages. This includes being watchful for any strangers who are going onto porches for no apparent reason, or following delivery trucks.

‚Ä¢ Ask the shipper to hold your package at their facility. Most offer this service.

‚Ä¢ Track deliveries online. Many offer a text notification to your cell phone when a package has been delivered.

‚Ä¢ Request a signature confirmation of delivery.

‚Ä¢ Insure valuable items.

‚Ä¢ Provide delivery instructions. If packages will be left while you are not home, try to have them left out of sight from the street.

If you see the crime in progress, use caution and do not approach the suspect(s), instead call 911. When calling 911 please keep in mind that it is important to give as much information as possible that describes the potential suspect(s), their vehicles, and direction of travel.

Be safe and if you see something say something by calling us. 911 for life threatening emergencies or crimes in progress or 408-615-5580 for non-emergencies.
